cial media entertainment has expanded rapidly and the traditional entertainment industry has been forced to cede significant power and influence to content creators, their fans, and subscribers. Digital platforms have created a natural market for embedded advertising, changing the worlds of marketing and communication in their wake. Combined, these factors have produced new, radically shifting demands on the entertainment industry, posing new challenges for screen regimes, media scholars, industry professionals, content creators, and audiences alike.Stuart Cunningham and David Craig chronicle the rise of social media entertainment and its impact on media consumption and production. A massive, industry-defining study with insight from over 100 industry insiders, Social Media Entertainment explores the latest transformations in the entertainment industry in this time of digital disruption.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aInternet entertainment industryzUnited States. 0aInternet entertainment industry-United States. 0aInternet entertainmentzUnited States. 0aInternet entertainment-United States. 0aSocial mediazUnited States. 0aSocial media-United States. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Industries / Media & Communications.2bisacsh  aAsian American creators.  aFacebook.  aIP control.  aInstagram.  aLGBTQ creators.  aMadison Avenue.  aMichelle Phan.  aNoCal.  aPewDiePie.  aSnapchat.  aSoCal.  aTwitter.  aVlogbrothers.  aYouTube.  aauthenticity.  abrand culture.  acontent creators.  acopyright industry high-control regimes.  acultural globalization.  acultural imperialism.  acultural politics.  agameplay.  alive-streamers.  alive-streaming platforms.  amedia globalization.  amedia management.  aminority representation.  anew screen ecology.  aplatform algorithms